# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bigyra
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] The Acanthocephala were long thought to be a discrete phylum.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] Recent genome analysis has shown that they are descended from, and should be considered as, highly modified rotifers.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] This unified taxon is sometimes known as Syndermata, or simply as Rotifera, with the acanthocephalans described as a subclass of a rotifer class Hemirotatoria.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] The earliest recognisable description of Acanthocephala – a worm with a proboscis armed with hooks – was made by Italian author Francesco Redi (1684).
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] In 1771, Joseph Koelreuter proposed the name Acanthocephala.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] Philipp Ludwig Statius Müller independently called them *Echinorhynchus* in 1776.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] Karl Rudolphi in 1809 formally named them Acanthocephala.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] The oldest known member of the group is the Middle Jurassic (living approximately 165 million years ago) taxon *Juracanthocephalus daohugouensis* known from the Jiulongshan Formation (China).
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] The fossil record of the group also includes eggs found in a coprolite from the Late Cretaceous Bauru Group of Brazil, around 70–80 million years old, likely from a crocodyliform.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] The group may have originated substantially earlier.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] Acanthocephalans are highly adapted to a parasitic mode of life, and have lost many organs and structures through evolutionary processes.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] This makes determining relationships with other higher taxa through morphological comparison problematic.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] A 2016 phylogenetic analysis of the gene order in the mitochondria suggests that Seisonidea and Acanthocephala are sister clades and that the Eurotatoria are the sister clade to this group, producing the cladogram below.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] Several morphological characteristics distinguish acanthocephalans from other phyla of parasitic worms.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] Acanthocephalans lack a mouth or alimentary canal.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] This is a feature they share with the cestoda (tapeworms), although the two groups are not closely related.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] Adult stages live in the intestines of their host and uptake nutrients which have been digested by the host, directly, through their body surface.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] The acanthocephalans lack an excretory system, although some species have been shown to possess flame cells (protonephridia).
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] The most notable feature of the acanthocephala is the presence of an anterior, protrudable proboscis that is usually covered with spiny hooks (hence the common name: thorny or spiny headed worm).
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] The proboscis bears rings of recurved hooks arranged in horizontal rows, and it is by means of these hooks that the animal attaches itself to the tissues of its host.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] The hooks may be of two or three shapes, usually: longer, more slender hooks are arranged along the length of the proboscis, with several rows of more sturdy, shorter nasal hooks around the base of the proboscis.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] The proboscis is used to pierce the gut wall of the final host, and hold the parasite fast while it completes its life cycle.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] Like the body, the proboscis is hollow, and its cavity is separated from the body cavity by a *septum* or *proboscis sheath*.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] Traversing the cavity of the proboscis are muscle-strands inserted into the tip of the proboscis at one end and into the septum at the other.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] Their contraction causes the proboscis to be invaginated into its cavity.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] The whole proboscis apparatus can also be, at least partially, withdrawn into the body cavity, and this is effected by two retractor muscles which run from the posterior aspect of the septum to the body wall.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] Some of the acanthocephalans (perforating acanthocephalans) can insert their proboscis in the intestine of the host and open the way to the abdominal cavity.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] The size of these animals varies greatly, ranging from a few millimetres in length to *Macracanthorhynchus hirudinaceus*, which measures from 10 to 65 centimetres (3.9 to 25.6 in).
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] A curious feature shared by both larva and adult is the large size of many of the cells, e.g. the nerve cells and cells forming the uterine bell.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] Polyploidy is common, with up to 343n having been recorded in some species.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] The body surface of the acanthocephala is peculiar.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] Externally, the skin has a thin tegument that covers the epidermis and consists of a syncytium with no cell walls.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] The syncytium is traversed by a series of branching tubules containing fluid and is controlled by a few wandering, amoeboid nuclei.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] Inside the syncytium is an irregular layer of circular muscle fibres, and within this again some rather scattered longitudinal fibres; there is no endothelium.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] In their micro-structure the muscular fibres resemble those of nematodes.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] Except for the absence of the longitudinal fibres the skin of the proboscis resembles that of the body, but the fluid-containing tubules of the proboscis are shut off from those of the body.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] The canals of the proboscis open into a circular vessel which runs round its base.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] From the circular canal two sac-like projections called the *lemnisci* run into the cavity of the body, alongside the proboscis cavity.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] Each consists of a prolongation of the syncytial material of the proboscis skin, penetrated by canals and sheathed with a muscular coat.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] They seem to act as reservoirs into which the fluid which is used to keep the proboscis "erect" can withdraw when it is retracted, and from which the fluid can be driven out when it is wished to expand the proboscis.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] The central ganglion of the nervous system lies behind the proboscis sheath or septum.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] It innervates the proboscis and projects two stout trunks posteriorly which supply the body.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] Each of these trunks is surrounded by muscles, and this nerve-muscle complex is called a *retinaculum*.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] In the male at least there is also a genital ganglion.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] Some scattered papillae may possibly be sense-organs.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] Acanthocephalans have complex life cycles, involving a number of hosts, for both developmental and resting stages.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] Complete life cycles have been worked out for only 25 species.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] The Acanthocephala are dioecious (an individual organism is either male or female).
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] There is a structure called the *genital ligament* which runs from the posterior end of the proboscis sheath to the posterior end of the body.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] In the male, two testes lie on either side of this.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] Each opens in a vas deferens which bears three diverticula or *vesiculae seminales*.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] The male also possesses three pairs of cement glands, found behind the testes, which pour their secretions through a duct into the vasa deferentia.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] These unite and end in a penis which opens posteriorly.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] In the female, the ovaries are found, like the testes, as rounded bodies along the ligament.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] From the ovaries, masses of ova dehisce into the body cavity, floating in its fluids for fertilization by male's sperm.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] After fertilization, each egg contains a developing embryo.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] (These embryos hatch into first stage larva.) The fertilized eggs are brought into the uterus by actions of the *uterine bell*, a funnel like opening continuous with the uterus.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] At the junction of the bell and the uterus there is a second, smaller opening situated dorsally.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] The bell "swallows" the matured eggs and passes them on into the uterus.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] (Immature embryos are passed back into the body cavity through the dorsal opening.) From the uterus, mature eggs leave the female's body via her oviduct, pass into the host's alimentary canal and are expelled from the host's body within feces.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] Having been expelled by the female, the acanthocephalan egg is released along with the feces of the host.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] For development to occur, the egg, containing the acanthor, needs to be ingested by an arthropod, usually a crustacean (there is one known life cycle which uses a mollusc as a first intermediate host).
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] Inside the intermediate host, the acanthor is released from the egg and develops into an acanthella.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] It then penetrates the gut wall, moves into the body cavity, encysts, and begins transformation into the infective cystacanth stage.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] This form has all the organs of the adult save the reproductive ones.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] The parasite is released when the first intermediate host is ingested.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] This can be by a suitable final host, in which case the cystacanth develops into a mature adult, or by a paratenic host, in which the parasite again forms a cyst.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] When consumed by a suitable final host, the cycstacant *excysts*, everts its proboscis and pierces the gut wall.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] It then feeds, grows and develops its sexual organs.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] The male uses the excretions of its *cement glands* to plug the vagina of the female, preventing subsequent matings from occurring.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] Embryos develop inside the female, and the life cycle repeats.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] Thorny-headed worms begin their life cycle inside invertebrates that reside in marine or freshwater systems.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] One example is *Polymorphus paradoxus.* *Gammarus lacustris*, a small crustacean that inhabits ponds and rivers, is one invertebrate that *P. paradoxus* may occupy; ducks are one of the definitive hosts.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] This crustacean is preyed on by ducks and hides by avoiding light and staying away from the surface.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] However, infection by *P. paradoxus* changes its behavior and appearance in a number of ways that increase its chance of being eaten.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] First, infection significantly reduces *G. lacustris'*s photophobia; as a result, it becomes attracted toward light and swims to the surface.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] Second, an infected organism will even go so far as to find a rock or a plant on the surface, clamp its mouth down, and latch on, making it easy prey for the duck.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] Finally, infection reduces the pigment distribution and amount in *G. lacustris,* causing the host to turn blue; unlike their normal brown colour, this makes the crustacean stand out and increases the chance the duck will see it.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] Experiments have shown that altered serotonin levels are likely responsible for at least some of these changes in behaviour.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] One experiment found that serotonin induces clinging behavior in *G. lacustris* similar to that seen in infected organisms.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] Another showed that infected *G. lacustris* had approximately 3 times as many serotonin-producing sites in its ventral nerve cord.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] Acanthocephalosis, a disease caused by *Acanthacephalus* infection, is prevalent in aquaculture, occurring in Atlantic salmon, rainbow and brown trout, tilapia, and tambaqui.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] Increasing occurrence in Brazilian farming of tambaqui has been reported, and in 2003 *Acanthacephalus* was first reported in cultured red snapper in Taiwan.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] The life cycle of *Polymorphus* spp. normally occurs between sea ducks (e.g. eiders and scoters) and small crabs.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] Infections found in commercial-sized lobsters in Canada were probably acquired from crabs that form an important dietary item of lobsters.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] Cystacanths occurring in lobsters can cause economic loss to fishermen.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] There are no known methods of prevention or control.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] Although they rarely infect humans, worms in the phylum Acanthocephala cause the disease acanthocephaliasis in humans.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] The earliest known infection was found in a prehistoric man in Utah.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] This infection was dated to 1869 ± 160 BC.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] The species involved was thought to be *Moniliformis clarki* which is still common in the area.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] The first report of an isolate in historic times was by Lambl in 1859 when he isolated *Macracanthorhynchus hirudinaceus* from a child in Prague.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] Lindemann in 1865 reported that this organism was commonly isolated in Russia.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] The reason for this was discovered by Schneider in 1871 when he found that an intermediate host, the scarabaeid beetle grub, was commonly eaten raw.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] The first report of clinical symptoms was by Calandruccio who in 1888 while in Italy infected himself by ingesting larvae.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] He reported gastrointestinal disturbances and shed eggs in two weeks.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] Subsequent natural infections have since been reported.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] Eight species have been isolated from humans to date.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] *Moniliformis moniliformis* is the most common isolate.
[src:bigyra/acanthocephala] Other isolates include *Acanthocephalus bufonis* and *Corynosoma strumosum*.
[src:bigyra/acidobacteriota] Members of this phylum are physiologically diverse, and can be found in a variety of environments including soil, decomposing wood, hot springs, oceans, caves, and metal-contaminated soils.
[src:bigyra/acidobacteriota] The members of this phylum are particularly abundant in soil habitats representing up to 52% of the total bacterial community.
[src:bigyra/acidobacteriota] Environmental factors such as pH and nutrients have been seen to drive Acidobacteriota dynamics.
[src:bigyra/acidobacteriota] Many Acidobacteriota are acidophilic, including the first described member of the phylum, *Acidobacterium capsulatum*.
[src:bigyra/acidobacteriota] There is much that is unknown about Acidobacteria both in their form and function.
[src:bigyra/acidobacteriota] Thus, this is a growing field of microbiology.
[src:bigyra/acidobacteriota] Some of this uncertainty can be attributed to the difficulty with which these bacteria are grown in the laboratory.
[src:bigyra/acidobacteriota] There has been recent success in propagation by using low concentrations of nutrients in combination with high amounts of CO2, yet, progress is still quite slow.
[src:bigyra/acidobacteriota] These new methods have only allowed approximately 30% of subdivisions to have species documented.
[src:bigyra/acidobacteriota] Additionally, many of the samples sequenced do not have taxonomic names as they have not yet been fully characterized.
[src:bigyra/acidobacteriota] This area of study is a very current topic, and scientific understanding is expected to grow and change as new information comes to light.
[src:bigyra/acidobacteriota] Other notable species are *Holophaga foetida*, *Geothrix fermentans*, *Acanthopleuribacter pedis* and *Bryobacter aggregatus*.
[src:bigyra/acidobacteriota] Since they have only recently been discovered and the large majority have not been cultured, the ecology and metabolism of these bacteria is not well understood.
[src:bigyra/acidobacteriota] However, these bacteria may be an important contributor to ecosystems, since they are particularly abundant within soils.
[src:bigyra/acidobacteriota] Members of subdivisions 1, 4, and 6 are found to be particularly abundant in soils.
[src:bigyra/acidobacteriota] As well as their natural soil habitat, unclassified subdivision 2 Acidobacteriota have also been identified as a contaminant of DNA extraction kit reagents, which may lead to their erroneous appearance in microbiota or metagenomic datasets.
[src:bigyra/acidobacteriota] Members of subdivision 1 have been found to dominate in low pH conditions.
[src:bigyra/acidobacteriota] Additionally, Acidobacteriota from acid mine drainage have been found to be more adapted to acidic pH conditions (pH 2–3) compared to Acidobacteriota from soils, potentially due to cell specialization and enzyme stability.
[src:bigyra/acidobacteriota] The G+C content of Acidobacteria genomes are consistent within their subdivisions - above 60% for group V fragments and roughly 10% lower for group III fragments.
[src:bigyra/acidobacteriota] The majority of Acidobacteriota are considered aerobes.
[src:bigyra/acidobacteriota] There are some Acidobacteriota that are considered anaerobes within subdivision 8 and subdivision 23.
[src:bigyra/acidobacteriota] It has been found that some strains of Acidobacteriota originating from soils have the genomic potential to respire oxygen at atmospheric and sub-atmospheric concentrations.
[src:bigyra/acidobacteriota] Members of the *Acidobacteriota* phylum have been considered oligotrophic bacteria due to high abundances in low organic carbon environments.
[src:bigyra/acidobacteriota] However, the variation in this phylum may indicate that they may not have the same ecological strategy.
[src:bigyra/acidobacteriota] The first species, *Acidobacterium capsulatum*, of this phylum was discovered in 1991.
[src:bigyra/acidobacteriota] However, Acidobacteriota were not recognized as a distinct clade until 1997, and were not recognized as a phylum until 2012.
[src:bigyra/acidobacteriota] In an effort to further classify Acidobacteria, 16S rRNA gene regions were sequenced from many different strains.
[src:bigyra/acidobacteriota] These sequences lead to the formation of subdivisions within the phyla.
[src:bigyra/acidobacteriota] Today, there are 26 accepted subdivisions recognized in the Ribosomal Database Project.
[src:bigyra/acidobacteriota] Much of this variety comes from populations of acidobacteria found in soils contaminated with uranium.
[src:bigyra/acidobacteriota] Therefore, most of the known species in this phyla are concentrated in a few of the subdivisions, the largest being #1.
[src:bigyra/acidobacteriota] Most of these microbes are aerobes, and they are all heterotrophic.
[src:bigyra/acidobacteriota] Subdivision 1 contains 11 of the known genera in addition to the majority of the species that have been able to be cultivated thus far.
[src:bigyra/acidobacteriota] Within the 22 known genera, there are 40 conclusive species.
[src:bigyra/acidobacteriota] The genera are divided amongst subdivisions 3, 4, 8, 10, 23, and 1.
[src:bigyra/acidobacteriota] As the Acidobateria are a developing area of microbiology, it is hypothesized that these numbers will change drastically with further study.
[src:bigyra/acidobacteriota] Some members of subdivision 1 are able to use D-glucose, D-xylose, and lactose as carbon sources, but are unable to use fucose or sorbose.
[src:bigyra/acidobacteriota] Members of subdivision 1 also contain enzymes such as galactosidases used in the breakdown of sugars.
[src:bigyra/acidobacteriota] Members of subdivision 4 have been found to use chitin as a carbon source.
[src:bigyra/acidobacteriota] Despite the presence of genetic information generally known to encode for carbohydrate processing machinery in various genera of Acidobacteria, several experimental studies have demonstrated the inability to break down various polysaccharides.
[src:bigyra/acidobacteriota] Cellulose is the main component of plant cell walls and a seemingly opportune resource for carbon.
[src:bigyra/acidobacteriota] However, only a single species across all subdivisions has been shown to process it, *Telmactobacter bradus* from subvision 1.
[src:bigyra/acidobacteriota] Researchers believe that an additional factor in the lack of understanding of carbon degradation by acidobacteria may stem from the present limited ability to provide adequate cultivation conditions.
[src:bigyra/acidobacteriota] To study the natural behavior of these bacteria, they must grow and live in a controlled, observable environment.
[src:bigyra/acidobacteriota] If such a habitat cannot be provided, recorded data cannot reliably report on the activity of the microbes in question.
[src:bigyra/acidobacteriota] Therefore, the inconsistencies between genome sequence based predictions and observed carbon processes may be explained by present study methods.
[src:bigyra/acidobacteriota] There has been no clear evidence that Acidobacteriota are involved in nitrogen-cycle processes such as nitrification, denitrification, or nitrogen fixation.
[src:bigyra/acidobacteriota] However, *Geothrix fermantans* was shown to be able to reduce nitrate and contained the norB gene.
[src:bigyra/acidobacteriota] The NorB gene was also identified in *Koribacter verstailis* and *Solibacter usitatus*.
[src:bigyra/acidobacteriota] In addition, the presence of the nirA gene has been observed in members of subdivision 1.
[src:bigyra/acidobacteriota] Additionally, to date, all genomes have been described to directly uptake ammonium via ammonium channel transporter family genes.
[src:bigyra/acidobacteriota] Acidobacteriota can use both inorganic and organic nitrogen as their nitrogen sources.
[src:bigyra/acidobacteriota] The currently accepted taxonomy is based on the List of Prokaryotic names with Standing in Nomenclature and National Center for Biotechnology Information (NCBI).
[src:bigyra/acinetactis] The validity and classification of this genus is contested.
[src:bigyra/acinetactis] In 1914, Adolf Pascher cast doubt on *Acinetactis*, suggesting that it was a junior synonym of *Dimorpha mutans*.
[src:bigyra/acinetactis] Cavalier-Smith classified *Acinetactis* as a heliomonad in 1993.
[src:bigyra/acinetactis] Bass et al. suggested in 2009 that the genus was a cercozoan in the class Granofilosea.
[src:bigyra/acritarch] Acritarchs were originally defined as non-acid soluble (i.e. non-carbonate, non-siliceous) organic-walled microfossils consisting of a central cavity, and whose biological affinities cannot be determined with certainty.
[src:bigyra/acritarch] Most commonly they are composed of thermally altered acid-insoluble carbon compounds (kerogen).
[src:bigyra/acritarch] Acritarchs may include the remains of a wide range of quite different kinds of organisms—ranging from the egg cases of small metazoans to resting cysts of many kinds of chlorophyta (green algae).
[src:bigyra/acritarch] It is likely that most acritarch species from the Paleozoic represent various stages of the life cycle of algae that were ancestral to the dinoflagellates.
[src:bigyra/acritarch] The nature of the organisms associated with Precambrian acritarchs is generally not well understood, though many are probably related to unicellular marine algae.
[src:bigyra/acritarch] In theory, when the biological source (taxon) of an acritarch does become known, that particular microfossil is removed from the acritarchs and classified with its proper group.
[src:bigyra/acritarch] While the classification of acritarchs into form genera is entirely artificial, it is not without merit, as the form taxa show traits similar to those of genuine taxa—for example an 'explosion' in the Cambrian and a mass extinction at the end of the Permian.
[src:bigyra/acritarch] The informal group Acritarcha Evitt 1963 was originally divided into these Subgroups: Acanthomorphitae, Polygonomorphitae, Prismatomorphitae, Oömorphitae, Netromorphitae, Dinetromorphitae, Stephanomorphitae, Pteromorphitae, Herkomorphitae, Platymorphitae, Sphaeromorphitae, and Disphaeromorphitae.
[src:bigyra/acritarch] In the end, it may well be, as Moczydłowska et al. suggested in 2011, that many acritarchs will, in fact, turn out to be algae.
[src:bigyra/acritarch] Acritarchs are found in sedimentary rocks from the present back into the Archean.
[src:bigyra/acritarch] They are typically isolated from siliciclastic sedimentary rocks using hydrofluoric acid but are occasionally extracted from carbonate-rich rocks.
[src:bigyra/acritarch] They are excellent candidates for index fossils used for dating rock formations in the Paleozoic Era and when other fossils are not available.
[src:bigyra/acritarch] Because most acritarchs are thought to be marine (pre-Triassic), they are also useful for palaeoenvironmental interpretation.
[src:bigyra/acritarch] The Archean and earliest Proterozoic microfossils termed "acritarchs" may actually be prokaryotes.
[src:bigyra/acritarch] The earliest eukaryotic acritarchs known (as of 2020) are from between 1950 and 2150 million years ago.
[src:bigyra/acritarch] At about 1 billion years ago the organisms responsible for acritarchs started to increase in abundance, diversity, size, complexity of shape, and especially, the size and number of spines.
[src:bigyra/acritarch] Their populations crashed during periods of extensive worldwide glaciations that covered the majority of the planet, but they proliferated in the Cambrian explosion and reached their highest diversity in the Paleozoic.
[src:bigyra/acritarch] The increased spininess 1000 million years ago possibly resulted from the need for defense against predators, especially predators large enough to swallow them or tear them apart.
[src:bigyra/acritarch] Other groups of small organisms from the Neoproterozoic era also show signs of anti-predator defenses.
[src:bigyra/acritarch] Further evidence that acritarchs were subject to herbivory around this time comes from a consideration of taxon longevity.
[src:bigyra/acritarch] Approximately 1,000 million years ago, species longevity fell sharply, suggesting that predation pressure, probably by protist herbivores, became an important factor.
[src:bigyra/acritarch] Predation would have kept populations in check, meaning that some nutrients were left unused, and new niches were available for new species to occupy.
[src:bigyra/acritarch] There are over 900 described genera; the following is a partial list, from Fossilid.info.
[src:bigyra/actinomycetota] The **Actinomycetota** (previously known as **"Actinobacteria"**) are a diverse phylum of Gram-positive bacteria with high guanine-cytosine content (GC content or G+C content).
[src:bigyra/actinomycetota] They are of great importance to land flora because of their contributions to soil systems.
[src:bigyra/actinomycetota] In soil, they help decompose organic matter of dead organisms so the molecules can be taken up anew by plants.
[src:bigyra/actinomycetota] While this role is also played by fungi, actinomycetota are much smaller and likely do not occupy the same ecological niche.
[src:bigyra/actinomycetota] In this role, the colonies often grow extensive mycelia, as fungi do, and the name of an important order of the phylum, Actinomycetales (the actinomycetes), reflects that they were long believed to be fungi.
[src:bigyra/actinomycetota] Some soil actinomycetota (such as *Frankia*) live symbiotically with the plants whose roots pervade the soil, fixing nitrogen for the plants in exchange for access to some of the plant's saccharides.
[src:bigyra/actinomycetota] Other species, such as many members of the genus *Mycobacterium*, are important pathogens.
[src:bigyra/actinomycetota] Beyond the great interest in Actinomycetota for their soil role, much is yet to be learned about them.
[src:bigyra/actinomycetota] Although currently understood primarily as soil bacteria, they might be more abundant in fresh waters.
[src:bigyra/actinomycetota] Actinomycetota is one of the dominant bacterial phyla and contains one of the largest of bacterial genera: *Streptomyces*.
[src:bigyra/actinomycetota] *Streptomyces* and other actinomycetota are major contributors to biological buffering of soils.
[src:bigyra/actinomycetota] They are also the source of many antibiotics.
[src:bigyra/actinomycetota] Bacteria of the Actinomycetota genus *Bifidobacterium* are the most common in the microbiome of human infants.
[src:bigyra/actinomycetota] Although adults have fewer bifidobacteria, intestinal bifidobacteria help maintain the mucosal barrier and reduce lipopolysaccharides in the intestine.
[src:bigyra/actinomycetota] Although some of the largest and most complex bacterial cells belong to the Actinomycetota, the group of marine Actinomarinales has been described as possessing the smallest free-living prokaryotic cells.
[src:bigyra/actinomycetota] Some Siberian or Antarctic biofilms of these bacteria are said to have the longest lifespan of any organism on Earth, frozen in permafrost at around half a million years ago.
[src:bigyra/actinomycetota] Most actinomycetota of medical or economic significance are in class Actinomycetia, and belong to the order Actinomycetales.
[src:bigyra/actinomycetota] While many of these cause disease in humans, *Streptomyces* is notable as a source of antibiotics.
[src:bigyra/actinomycetota] Of those actinomycetota not in the Actinomycetales, *Gardnerella* is one of the most researched.
[src:bigyra/actinomycetota] Classification of *Gardnerella* is controversial, and MeSH catalogues it as both a Gram-positive and Gram-negative organism.
[src:bigyra/actinomycetota] Actinomycetota-derived antibiotics that are important in medicine include aminoglycosides, anthracyclines, chloramphenicol, macrolides, tetracyclines, etc.
[src:bigyra/actinomycetota] Actinomycetota have high guanine and cytosine content in their DNA.
[src:bigyra/actinomycetota] The GC content of actinomycetota can be as high as 70%, though some may have a low GC content.
[src:bigyra/actinomycetota] Analysis of glutamine synthetase sequence has been suggested for phylogenetic analysis of the Actinomycetota.
[src:bigyra/actinomycetota] The currently accepted taxonomy is based on the List of Prokaryotic names with Standing in Nomenclature (LPSN) and National Center for Biotechnology Information (NCBI).
[src:bigyra/actinophryid] The **actinophryids** are an order of heliozoa, a polyphyletic array of amoebae.
[src:bigyra/actinophryid] They are common in fresh water and occasionally found in marine and soil habitats.
[src:bigyra/actinophryid] Actinophryids are unicellular and roughly spherical in shape, with many axopodia that radiate outward from the cell body.
[src:bigyra/actinophryid] Axopodia are a type of pseudopodia that are supported by hundreds of microtubules arranged in interlocking spirals and forming a needle-like internal structure or axoneme.
[src:bigyra/actinophryid] Small granules, extrusomes, that lie under the membrane of the body and axopodia capture flagellates, ciliates and small metazoa that make contact with the arms.
[src:bigyra/actinophryid] Actinophryids are largely aquatic protozoa with a spherical cell body and many needle-like axopodia.
[src:bigyra/actinophryid] They resemble the shape of a sun due to this structure, which is the inspiration for their common name: heliozoa, or "sun-animalcules".
[src:bigyra/actinophryid] Their bodies, without arms, range in size from a few tens of micrometers to slightly under a millimeter across.
[src:bigyra/actinophryid] The outer region of cell body is often vacuolated.
[src:bigyra/actinophryid] The endoplasm of actinophryids is less vacuolated than the outer layer, and a sharp boundary layer may be seen by light microscopy.
[src:bigyra/actinophryid] The organisms can be either mononucleate, with a single, well defined nucleus in the center of the cell body, or multinucleate, with 10 or more nuclei located under the outer vacuolated layer of cytoplasm.
[src:bigyra/actinophryid] The cytoplasm of actinophryids is often granular, similar to that of *Amoeba*.
[src:bigyra/actinophryid] Actinophryid cells may fuse when feeding, creating larger aggregated organisms.
[src:bigyra/actinophryid] Fine granules that occur just under the cell membrane are used up when food vacuoles form to enclose prey.
[src:bigyra/actinophryid] Actinophryids may also form cysts when food is not readily available.
[src:bigyra/actinophryid] A layer of siliceous plates is deposited under the cell membrane during the encystment process.
[src:bigyra/actinophryid] Contractile vacuoles are common in these organisms, which are presumed to use them to maintain body volume by expelling fluids to compensate for the entry of water by osmosis.
[src:bigyra/actinophryid] Contractile vacuoles are visible as clear bulges from the surface of the cell body that slowly fill then rapidly deflate, expelling their contents into the environment.
[src:bigyra/actinophryid] The most distinctive characteristic of the actinophryids is their axopodia.
[src:bigyra/actinophryid] These axopodia consist of a central, rigid rod which is coated in a thin layer of ectoplasm.
[src:bigyra/actinophryid] In *Actinophrys* the axonemes end on the surface of the central nucleus, and in the multicellular *Actinosphaerium* they end at or near nuclei.
[src:bigyra/actinophryid] The axonemes are composed of microtubules arranged in a double spiral pattern characteristic of the order.
[src:bigyra/actinophryid] Due to their long, parallel construction, these microtubules demonstrate strong birefringence.
[src:bigyra/actinophryid] These axopodia are used for prey capture, in movement, cell fusion and perhaps division.
[src:bigyra/actinophryid] They are stiff but may flex especially near their tips, and are highly dynamic, undergoing frequent construction and destruction.
[src:bigyra/actinophryid] When used to collect prey items, two methods of capture have been noted, termed axopodial flow and rapid axopodial contraction.
[src:bigyra/actinophryid] Axopodial flow involves the slow movement of a prey item along the surface of the axopod as the ectoplasm itself moves, while rapid axopodial contraction involves the collapse of the axoneme's microtubule structure.
[src:bigyra/actinophryid] This behavior has been documented in many species, including *Actinosphaerium nucleofilum*, *Actinophrys sol*, and *Raphidiophrys contractilis*.
[src:bigyra/actinophryid] The rapid axopodial contraction occurs at high speed, often in excess of 5mm/s or tens of body lengths per second.
[src:bigyra/actinophryid] The axopodial contractions have been shown to be highly sensitive to environmental factors such as temperature and pressure as well as chemical signals like Ca2+ and colchicine.
[src:bigyra/actinophryid] Reproduction in actinophryids generally takes place via fission, where one parent cell divides into two or more daughter cells.
[src:bigyra/actinophryid] For multinucleate heliozoa, this process is plasmotomic as the nuclei are not duplicated prior to division.
[src:bigyra/actinophryid] It has been observed that reproduction appears to be a response to food scarcity, with an increased number of divisions following the removal of food and larger organisms during times of food excess.
[src:bigyra/actinophryid] Actinophryids also undergo autogamy during times of food scarcity.
[src:bigyra/actinophryid] This is better described as genetic reorganization than reproduction, as the number of individuals produced is the same as the initial number.
[src:bigyra/actinophryid] Nonetheless, it serves as a way to increase genetic diversity within an individual which may improve the likelihood of expressing favorable genetic traits.
[src:bigyra/actinophryid] Plastogamy has also been extensively documented in actinophryids, especially in multinucleate ones.
[src:bigyra/actinophryid] *Actinosphaerium* were observed to combine freely without the combination of nuclei, and this process sometimes resulted in more or less individuals than originally combined.
[src:bigyra/actinophryid] This process is not caused merely by contact between two individuals but can be caused by damage to the cell body.
[src:bigyra/actinophryid] Under unfavourable conditions, some species will form a cyst.
[src:bigyra/actinophryid] This is often the product of autogamy, in which case the cysts produced are zygotes.
[src:bigyra/actinophryid] Cells undergoing this process withdraw their axopodia, adhere to the substrate, and take on an opaque and grayish appearance.
[src:bigyra/actinophryid] This cyst then divides until only uninucleate cells remain.
[src:bigyra/actinophryid] The cyst wall is thickly layered 7–8 times and includes gelatinous layers, layers of silica plates, and iron.
[src:bigyra/actinophryid] Originally placed in Heliozoa (Sarcodina), the actinophryids are now understood to be part of the stramenopiles.
[src:bigyra/actinophryid] They are unrelated to centrohelid and desmothoracid heliozoa with which they had been previously classified.
[src:bigyra/actinophryid] There are several genera included within this classification.
[src:bigyra/actinophryid] *Actinophrys* are smaller and have a single, central nucleus.
[src:bigyra/actinophryid] Most have a cell body 40–50 micrometer in diameter with axopods around 100 μm in length, though this varies significantly.
[src:bigyra/actinophryid] *Actinosphaerium* are several times larger, from 200 to 1000 μm in diameter, with many nuclei and are found exclusively in fresh water.
[src:bigyra/actinophryid] A third genus, *Camptonema*, has a debated status.
[src:bigyra/actinophryid] It has been observed once and was treated as a junior subjective synonym of *Actinosphaerium* by Mikrjukov & Patterson in 2001, but as a valid genus by Cavalier-Smith & Scoble (2013).
[src:bigyra/actinophryid] *Heliorapha* is a further debated taxon, it being a new generic vehicle for the species *azurina* that was initially assigned to the genus *Ciliophrys*.
[src:bigyra/actinophryid] According to the latest review of actinophryid classifications, they are organized into two genera and six species.
[src:bigyra/bigyra] Bigyra is a diverse group of heterotrophic, mainly phagotrophic stramenopiles that lack cell walls.
[src:bigyra/bigyra] It contains three well-known important groups with widely different ecological functions and morphologies: labyrinthulomycetes, opalines and bicosoecids.
[src:bigyra/bigyra] Labyrinthulomycetes is a group of protists that absorb nutrients in an osmotrophic or phagotrophic manner.
[src:bigyra/bigyra] They can behave either as free-living amoebae or as mycelium-like networks of cytoplasmic threads.
[src:bigyra/bigyra] Some of them are saprotrophic decomposers of the detrital food web; as such, they play a role in making organic matter more accessible to other organisms.
[src:bigyra/bigyra] Others are parasitic, and others are predators of bacteria.
[src:bigyra/bigyra] They are cosmopolitan, ubiquitous in marine, freshwater and estuarine environments.
[src:bigyra/bigyra] They live in association with algae, marine plants and detritus.
[src:bigyra/bigyra] Opalinata is a diverse assemblage of modified parasitic protists known as 'opalines'.
[src:bigyra/bigyra] They inhabit the intestines of various animals, primarily amphibians.
[src:bigyra/bigyra] Among them, the opalinids are highly unusual protists: their large cells have numerous flagella and from two to hundreds of nuclei.
[src:bigyra/bigyra] Their cell surface is delicately folded, giving it an iridescent appearance (hence their name, a reference to the iridescent opal).
[src:bigyra/bigyra] Another important group of opalines is *Blastocystis*, a prevalent parasite of humans and other animals.
[src:bigyra/bigyra] Bicosoecida is a small group that contains free-living marine and freshwater nanoflagellates that feed on bacteria.
[src:bigyra/bigyra] They are present in every ecosystem, including extreme environments such as the deep sea or salt flats.
[src:bigyra/bigyra] They play a crucial role in the microbial food web by composing the link between bacteria and higher trophic levels.
[src:bigyra/bigyra] They are also important in biogeochemical cycles by remineralizing the nutrients.
[src:bigyra/bigyra] Their classification has changed multiple times over the years, and is still an unresolved issue.
[src:bigyra/bigyra] Bigyra contains many of the earliest-diverging clades of the Stramenopiles.
[src:bigyra/bigyra] The Stramenopiles are a supergroup of eukaryotic organisms (protists) characterized by the presence of an anterior flagellum with tripartite hairs, called mastigonemes.
[src:bigyra/bigyra] Together with Rhizaria and Alveolata, the Stramenopiles compose the SAR supergroup.
[src:bigyra/bigyra] All of Bigyra are heterotrophic microorganisms evolved from the last common ancestor of Stramenopiles, which is thought to have been phototrophic.
[src:bigyra/bigyra] Following this hypothesis, the bigyran ancestor would have secondarily lost their photosynthetic plastids.
[src:bigyra/bigyra] Some characteristics of bigyran groups can be explained by their origin from ancestral plastids.
[src:bigyra/bigyra] For example, labyrinthulomycetes can produce omega-3 poly-unsaturated fatty acids through a desaturase usually present in chloroplasts.
[src:bigyra/bigyra] Bigyra is composed of two subphyla: Opalozoa and Sagenista.
[src:bigyra/bigyra] Opalozoa is further subdivided into two groups: Placidozoa, which contains the opalines and three clades discovered through the detection of environmental DNA (Nanomonadea, Opalomonadea and Placididea), and the bicosoecid flagellates.
[src:bigyra/bigyra] Sagenista contains the labyrinthulomycetes and two environmental clades grouped under the name Eogyrea.
[src:bigyra/bigyra] The monophyly of Bigyra remains uncertain.
[src:bigyra/bigyra] The positions of the two bigyran clades (Opalozoa and Sagenista) are not consistent between the published studies, because they diverged from each other very early after the separation from the ancestor of all stramenopiles.
[src:bigyra/bigyra] This 'deep branching' makes it difficult to find the exact branching order of bigyran clades.
[src:bigyra/bigyra] Additionally, not all clades are well-represented by molecular data in these studies.
[src:bigyra/bigyra] Several studies support the monophyly of Bigyra.
[src:bigyra/bigyra] Bigyra was first described in 1997 by the protozoologist Thomas Cavalier-Smith as a phylum within Heterokonta (synonym of Stramenopiles).
[src:bigyra/bigyra] Bigyra was defined as organisms with the synapomorphy of a ciliary transition region (i.e. a structure that controls protein transport at the base of the flagellum) with structures in the shape of two helices or rings, hence the name 'bigyra' meaning 'double helix'.
[src:bigyra/bigyra] Opalinata, non-phagotrophic gut-symbiotes found in animals.
[src:bigyra/bigyra] Bigyromonada, phagotrophic zooflagellates.
[src:bigyra/bigyra] Their common ancestor was thought to have evolved from photosynthetic heterokonts, but would have secondarily lost its plastids, as opposed to the photosynthetic Ochrophyta which retain them.
[src:bigyra/bigyra] Bigyra was, at the time, postulated as a monophyletic group (or clade), evolved from a paraphyletic grade of ochrophyte classes.
[src:bigyra/bigyra] Posterior analyses completely changed the phylogeny of Stramenopiles.
[src:bigyra/bigyra] They revealed Pseudofungi and Bigyromonadea were more closely related to a monophyletic Ochrophyta than they were to Opalinata, meaning that the synapomorphy of a double helix could have been present in the common ancestor of all heterokonts.
[src:bigyra/bigyra] Sagenista, containing the osmotrophic Labyrinthulea.
[src:bigyra/bigyra] Bigyra was modified again in 2013 after the discovery of several environmental clades called MAST ('MArine STramenopiles').
[src:bigyra/bigyra] The subphylum Opalozoa assimilated the bicosoecids and an array of new clades: Placididea, Nanomonadea (MAST-3) and Opalomonadea (MAST-12).
[src:bigyra/bigyra] The subphylum Sagenista, on the other hand, received a new class Eogyrea that was composed of several MAST lineages not yet described.
[src:bigyra/bigyra] Later, one of the MAST clades within Eogyrea would be described as *Pseudophyllomitus* (MAST-6).
